  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(21) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Blessed are ye that hunger now.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—In the second beatitude, as in the first, we note the absence of the words that seem to give the blessing on those that “hunger and thirst after righteousness” its specially spiritual character. The law implied is obviously the same as before. Fulness of bread, a life abounding in comforts and luxuries, like that of the Rich Man in the parable of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 16:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", tends to dull the edge of appetite for higher things. Those who know what the hunger of the body is, can understand better, and are more likely to feel, the hunger of the soul.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Blessed are ye that weep now: for ye shall laugh.—The clause is remarkable as being (with its counterpart in Luke 6:25) the only instance in the New Testament of the use of “laughter” as the symbol of spiritual joy. In James 4:9 it comes in as representing worldly gladness; but the Greek word was too much associated with the lower forms of mirth to find ready acceptance. It is probable that the Aramaic word which our Lord used, like the mirth or laughter which entered into the name of Isaac (Genesis 21:6), had a somewhat higher meaning. Hebrew laughter was a somewhat graver thing than that of Greek or Roman. It had had no comedy to degrade it.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Blessed are ye that weep now: for ye shall laugh.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The clause is remarkable as being (with its counterpart in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 6:25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") the only instance in the New Testament of the use of “laughter” as the symbol of spiritual joy. In ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "James 4:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " it comes in as representing worldly gladness; but the Greek word was too much associated with the lower forms of mirth to find ready acceptance. It is probable that the Aramaic word which our Lord used, like the mirth or laughter which entered into the name of Isaac (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 21:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), had a somewhat higher meaning. Hebrew laughter was a somewhat graver thing than that of Greek or Roman. It had had no comedy to degrade it.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
